      content: `Contraception means preventing pregnancy. There are many methods available, so you can choose what works best for you.

**What is Contraception?**
- Birth control to prevent pregnancy
| Different methods work differently
| Some need a doctor's prescription
| Others are available without prescription

**Types of Contraception:**

**1. Barrier Methods**
- Condoms (male and female)
| Diaphragm
| Cervical cap
| Contraceptive sponge
| Prevent sperm from reaching egg

**2. Hormonal Methods**
- Birth control pills
| Patch
| Ring
| Shot (injection)
| Implant
| IUD (hormonal)
| Prevent ovulation or thicken cervical mucus

**3. Long-Acting Reversible Contraception (LARC)**
- IUDs (hormonal and copper)
| Implant
| Most effective methods
| Last for years

**4. Permanent Methods**
| Tubal ligation (female)
| Vasectomy (male)
| For people sure they don't want more children

**5. Fertility Awareness**
| Tracking your cycle
| Avoiding sex during fertile time
| Requires careful tracking

**6. Emergency Contraception**
| Morning-after pill
| Can prevent pregnancy after unprotected sex
| Use as soon as possible (within 5 days)

**Effectiveness:**
| Most effective: IUDs, implant, sterilization (>99%)
| Very effective: pills, patch, ring (91-99%)
| Less effective: condoms, fertility awareness (72-88%)

**Remember:** No method is 100% perfect. Using condoms also protects against sexually transmitted infections.`,
